Mothe traces this attitude to formative moments of the field in which philosophers relied upon the practice of writing to mediate between the study of “religion,” on the one hand, and “theology,” on the other. In the second part, LaMothe revives the work of theologian, phenomenologist, and historian of religion Gerardus van der Leeuw for help in interpreting how dancing can serve as a medium of religious experience and expression. In so doing, LaMothe opens new perspectives on the role of bodily being in religious life, and on the place of theology in the study of religion.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Dance / General.2bisacsh1 aHegel, G. W. F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKierkegaard, Søren, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLeeuw, Gerardus van der, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchleiermacher, Friedrich, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z97831107072980 cprintz978082322403640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978082329104540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823291045423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780823291045/original  a978-3-11-070729-8  Fordham University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK